<h2>Thermometric Calibration</h2>

<p>An essential component of blackbody design and integration is the accurate,
end-to-end calibration of the resistance thermometer devices (RTDs) used to
sense temperature. Ideally, the calibration should be performed on the
blackbody, the blackbody electronics and the interconnecting harness as
a complete assembly, particularly if the RTDs have been surface mounted or
encapsulated using adhesives or potting compounds (typical for
space-engineered components). The CTE mismatch between the sensor, the
substrate and the bonding or potting material will induce stress, and
therefore strain, in the restrained RTDs, resulting in shifts in the
resistance-versus-temperature curves as sensors are temperature cycled.
Thermal conditioning and the judicious choice of retraining material can do
much to minimise these shifts, making accurate, long-term calibration
possible, but extremely time-consuming. </p>

<p>It should be noted that for space-engineered blackbodies, the time
interval between thermometric calibration and launch could be as much
as 4 years with an additional 5 to 10 years of operational life on
orbit. In addition, the thermometers and their conditioning and
read-out electronics must be able to survive high levels of shock and
vibration and the hostile environment of space, all without undergoing
a shift in calibration.</p>
