<p>The cryostat was also used to calibrate meteorological sensors for the
<a href="http://www.beagle2.com/index.htm">BEAGLE 2 Mars
Lander</a>. The payload includes two air temperature sensors and an
Oxford-designed <a
href="../../user/wilson/B2WS/">wind sensor</a>. The
air temperature sensors and the resistance-temperature dependence of
the anemometer films were calibrated in the cryostat, Fig
4. Aerodynamic calibration of the wind sensor was performed in a <a
href="../../user/wilson/matacf.html">low density
wind tunnel</a>, which is located at the Department of Engineering
Science, Oxford University.</p>

<p>In addition to the cryostat for small blackbodies, the department
has acquired a second, LHe-cooled cryostat with a working temperature
range from 1.5&#160;K to 300&#160;K. The cryostat, the rewiring and
recommisioning of whcih is shown in Fig&#160;5, is used to calibrate
4-wire cryogenic resistance thermometers, such as the 27&#160;ohm
ceramic rhodium-iron resistance thermometers (RIRTs) used for <a
href="2point2_metre_facility/targets_5.html">HIRDLS radiometric test and
calibration</a>. The department's a.c. resistance bridges, resistance
standards and other thermometry test equipment are listed below. The
LHe cryostat's thermometer block also has two Tinsley 5187L capsule
gas-filled PRTs and two Tinsley 5187U capsule gas-filled RIRTs. These
will require recalibration before the cryostat can be considered
operational.</p>

